    <h1>6 SOUTH AFRICA</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201222/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-22"><time>2020-12-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TRAVEL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Nokuthula Ma­jozi, sous chef at Rose­wood Ho­tel and se­nior pie-maker at Hol­born Din­ing Room in Lon­don</p>
    <p>Christ­mas is a huge cel­e­bra­tion for friends, fam­ily and the whole com­mu­nity, with strangers also in­vited to share in this tra­di­tion.</p>
    <p>In Dur­ban, South Africa, my mother and aun­ties would wake up as early as 4am to start cook­ing – pro­duc­ing a house­ful of flavours such as masala, ginger, gar­lic and cin­na­mon for a vege­tar­ian dish called chakalaka.</p>
    <p>As kids, we would have a quick break­fast and rush out­side to meet other kids in the neigh­bour­hood to play a game about the sun danc­ing and chang­ing colours.</p>
    <p>Dressed in our new clothes, we would then visit one an­other and col­lect food and sweets, such as but­tery bis­cuits, as gifts.</p>
    <p>On my Christ­mas ta­ble: Malva pud­ding. Made of apri­cot jam, this spongy caramelise­d pud­ding is served hot with cus­tard cream sauce in a big bowl.</p>

